                <h5 style="color: yellow; text-decoration: underline; text-align: center;">HTML ARTICLE: UNDERSTANDING HTML IFRAME AND COMPUTER CODE ELEMENTS</h5>
                <p><strong>Author:</strong> Benayahu Yakuba</p>
                <p><strong>Published:</strong> October 10, 2023</p>
                <p><strong>Last Updated:</strong> November 5, 2023</p>
                <p><strong>Category:</strong> Web Development</p>
                <p><strong>Tags:</strong> HTML, iframes, coding</p>
                <h3 style="color: white; padding-left: 1vw;"><u>HTML Iframe</u></h3>
                <p>
                    An HTML iframe element; short for "inline frame",  is used to <strong>embed another HTML document or web page within the current document.</strong>
                    It allows you to display content from an external source, such as a different website or web application, directly within your webpage.
                    Here is WDD iframe example: 
                </p>
                <iframe style="width: 50vw; height: 30vh; background-color: white; border: none; margin-left: 5vw;" src="htmlcss1.html" 
                name="wdd_iframe" title="iframe example"></iframe>
                <p><a style="width: 5vw; background-color: black;" href="htmlcss1.html" target="wdd_iframe" title="iframe example">visit WDD</a></p>
                <h3 style="color: white; padding-left: 1vw;"><u>HTML Computer Code Elements</u></h3>
                <p>
                    In HTML, there are several elements and tags that are used to represent computer code within a document. 
                    These elements are primarily used for displaying code snippets, programming examples,
                    or any text that should be presented in a monospace (fixed-width) font to maintain formatting.
                    Here are some of the key HTML elements for displaying computer code:
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <code>&lt;code&gt;</code> element - Used for inline sections of code.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> element - Used for displaying blocks of code or text with preserved formatting.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <code>&lt;kbd&gt;</code> element -  Used for indicating keyboard input.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <code>&lt;samp&gt;</code> element - Used for representing sample output from a program or script.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <code>&lt;var&gt;</code> element - Used for indicating variables or placeholders in code.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <u><code>&lt;code&gt;</code> element example: List comprehension in Python</u>
                    <pre>
                            <code style="color: black;">
                            i = 10
                            print([x**2 for x in range(1, i)])
                            This will print the squares of values from 1 to 9
                            </code>
                    </pre><br>
                    <u style="padding-left: 1vw;"><code>&lt;kbd&gt;</code> element example:  Saving page:</u> Save the document by pressing <kbd style="color: yellow;">CTRL + S</kbd><br><br>
                    <u style="padding-left: 1vw;"><code>&lt;samp&gt;</code> element example:  Computer output: </u> <samp style="color: yellow;">  File not found. Press F1 to continue</samp><br><br>
                    <u style="padding-left: 1vw;"><code>&lt;var&gt;</code> element example: </u>  Area of a square is found by: π x <var style="color: yellow;">r²</var> - where r is the radius of the square
                </p>
                <!-- Examples on details, summary,figure, fuigcaption, and time elements -->
